'''Scott Cooke McCreery'''<ref name="10 Things pg. 2">{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-things-2/|first=Billy|last=Dukes|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Scotty McCreery|work=[[Townsquare Media|Taste of Country]]|date=October 8, 2012 |access-date=April 8, 2014}}</ref> (born October 9, 1993) is an American [[country music|country]] singer. He rose to fame after winning the [[American Idol (season 10)|tenth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]'' in May 2011.

His debut studio album, ''[[Clear as Day]]'', was released in October 2011 and was certified platinum in the United States. The album includes the top 20 country songs, "[[I Love You This Big]]" and "[[The Trouble with Girls (song)|The Trouble with Girls]]". McCreery released a Christmas album, ''[[Christmas with Scotty McCreery]]'', in October 2012 and it has been certified gold. He released his third album, ''[[See You Tonight]]'', in October 2013. Its [[See You Tonight (song)|title track]] became his first single to reach the top ten on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'s ''Country charts. Setting a new record in July 2017 with his single "[[Five More Minutes (Scotty McCreery song)|Five More Minutes]]",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://headlineplanet.com/home/2017/08/06/scotty-mccreery-chris-stapleton-songs-debut-mediabase-country-radio-chart/|title=Scotty McCreery, Chris Stapleton Songs Debut On Mediabase Country Radio Chart|date=August 6, 2017|website=Headlineplanet.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> McCreery became the only country music artist in Country Aircheck/Media base history to chart a song without the backing of a record label;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2017/08/17/scotty-mccreery-sets-chart-record-scores-record-deal/578032001/|title=Scotty McCreery sets chart record, scores record deal|website=The Tennessean|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> it topped ''Billboard'' in February 2018.  His fourth album, ''[[Seasons Change (Scotty McCreery album)|Seasons Change]]'', was released in March 2018 and became McCreery's fourth top 10 album in the United States.<ref name="BB200">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8260857/xxxtentacion-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title=XXXTentacion's '?' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=March 25, 2018|access-date=March 26, 2018}}</ref> His fifth album, ''[[Same Truck]]'', was released on September 17, 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/country/future-releases|title=Future Releases for Country Radio Stations|website=AllAccess|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210826083218/https://www.allaccess.com/country/future-releases|archivedate=August 26, 2021|accessdate=October 20, 2021}}</ref>

In 2024, McCreery received one of country music's crowning achievements when he became a [[List of Grand Ole Opry members|member]] of the [[Grand Ole Opry]]. He was inducted on April 20 by his childhood hero [[Josh Turner]].

==Early life==
McCreery was born on October 9, 1993, in [[Garner, North Carolina]], the son of Judy (née Cooke) and Michael McCreery.<ref name="In the Tour Bus">{{cite web|url=http://houstonlifestyles.com/scotty-mccreery/|first=Melanie|last=Saxton|title=In the Tour Bus with Scotty McCreery|work=Houston Lifestyles & Homes|date=May 1, 2013|access-date=April 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnewsnashville.com/scotty-mccreery-items-on-exhibit-at-north-carolina-museum/|first=Dan|last=Harr|title=Scotty McCreery Items on Exhibit at North Carolina Museum|work=Music News Nashville|date=October 4, 2012|access-date=April 8, 2014|archive-date=November 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107021918/http://www.musicnewsnashville.com/scotty-mccreery-items-on-exhibit-at-north-carolina-museum/|url-status=dead}}</ref> His parents originally planned on naming him Evan, but changed their minds on their way to the hospital.<ref name="10 Things pg. 2"/> McCreery is of one quarter [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] descent; his father, a manufacturing systems analyst for [[Schneider Electric]], was born in [[Aguadilla, Puerto Rico|Aguadilla]], Puerto Rico, to a military father and a Puerto Rican mother from [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]], both of whom later moved to [[Aberdeen, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5XKbTTdwNww | archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211118/5XKbTTdwNww| archive-date=2021-11-18 | url-status=live|title=EXCLUSIVE: Idol Front Runner Scotty McCreery Tells Us What He Has in Common and who With J.Lo|magazine=Latina magazine| date=March 9, 2011|via=YouTube|access-date=April 2, 2011}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref name="This is my new life!">{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/idolchatter/post/2011/05/scotty-exit-interview/1|title='Idol' winner Scotty McCreery: 'This is my new life!' |first=Lindsay |last=Deutsch | work=USA Today | date=May 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name="The Pilot">{{cite web|url=http://thepilot.www.clients.ellingtoncms.com/news/2011/feb/16/could-he-be-the-next-american-idol/ |title=Could He Be The Next American Idol? |publisher=The Pilot |date=February 16, 2011 |access-date=April 16, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420155221/http://thepilot.www.clients.ellingtoncms.com/news/2011/feb/16/could-he-be-the-next-american-idol/|archive-date=April 20, 2011}}</ref> McCreery's mother is a real estate agent for Fonville Morisey.<ref name="Garnerclayton">{{cite web|url=http://www.garnerclayton.com/2011/05/25/7044/everyone-in-garner-sings-scottys.html|first=Thad|last=Ogburn|title=Everyone in Garner sings Scotty's praise|work=Garner-Cleveland Record|date=May 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426000619/http://www.garnercleveland.com/2011/05/25/7044/everyone-in-garner-sings-scottys.html|archive-date=April 26, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.countrymusicchannel.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/latest-news/interview--scotty-mccreery |title=Interview: Scotty McCreery |publisher=XYZnetworks Pty., Ltd |access-date=June 18, 2012 |archive-date=November 9, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109162939/http://www.countrymusicchannel.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/latest-news/interview--scotty-mccreery |url-status=dead }}</ref> She also owns a [[tanning salon]] in [[Clayton, North Carolina]].<ref name="Garnerclayton"/> McCreery's older sister, Ashley, attended [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte|UNC Charlotte]].<ref name="The Pilot"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/lifestyles/travel/blogpost/9622991/ |title=Best Scotty Story |date=May 20, 2011 |publisher=WRAL.com |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> Both were raised in Garner.<ref name="The Pilot"/><ref name="gac">{{Cite web |title=Scotty McCreery Biography |url=http://www.gactv.com/gac/ar_artists_a-z/article/0,3028,GAC_26071_6041946_02,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025185027/http://www.gactv.com/gac/ar_artists_a-z/article/0,3028,GAC_26071_6041946_02,00.html |archive-date=October 25, 2011 |access-date=June 18, 2012 |publisher=Scripps Networks, LLC.}}</ref><ref name="CMT">{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.ca/artist/scotty-mccreery/|title=Scotty McCreery Biography|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|access-date=April 14, 2014|archive-date=May 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529082217/http://www.cmt.ca/artist/scotty-mccreery|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Around the age of five or six, McCreery received a book about [[Elvis Presley]] from his grandmother, and Elvis became McCreery's earliest musical influence.<ref>{{cite AV media|people=Scotty McCreery|date=April 29, 2013|title=Elvis Fan and Country Singer Scotty McCreery Visits Graceland|url=http://www.elvis.com/news/detail.aspx?id=7020|access-date=April 11, 2014|work=elvis.com}}</ref><ref name="Talks Elvis, Gaga">{{cite web|url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/reality-rocks/scotty-mccreery-talks-elvis-gaga-making-his-mama-cry-and-being-normal-in-an-abnormal-pop-world.html|first=Lyndsey|last=Parker|title=Scotty McCreery Talks Elvis, Gaga, Making His Mama Cry, and Being Normal in an Abnormal Pop World|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=November 2, 2011|access-date=April 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Impersonated Elvis">{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/american-idol-scotty-mccreery-impersonate-elvis-presley/|first=Amy|last=Sciarretto|title='American Idol' Contestant Scotty McCreery Impersonated Elvis Presley as a Boy|work=Taste of Country|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=April 11, 2014}}</ref> He began learning guitar when he was around nine or ten years old.<ref name="Garnerclayton"/><ref name="Icon Competition">{{cite web|url=http://www.garnercitizen.com/2009/11/20/garner-teen-to-compete-in-high-school-icon-competition/|title=Garner teen to compete in high school icon competition|work=GarnerCitizen.com|date=November 20, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711072654/http://www.garnercitizen.com/2009/11/20/garner-teen-to-compete-in-high-school-icon-competition/|archive-date=July 11, 2011}}</ref>

McCreery attended Timber Drive Elementary School in Garner, West Lake Middle School in [[Apex, North Carolina|Apex]], and [[Garner Magnet High School]].<ref name="Garnerclayton"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.garnernews.net/view/full_story/11597412/article-McCreery-moves-onto-top-40--will-find-out-fate-tonight?instance=home_news_lead |title=McCreery moves onto top 40, will find out fate tonight |publisher=Garner News |date=February 25, 2011 |access-date=March 12, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806231744/http://www.garnernews.net/view/full_story/11597412/article-McCreery-moves-onto-top-40--will-find-out-fate-tonight?instance=home_news_lead|archive-date=August 6, 2011}}</ref> He participated in all three schools' choruses,<ref name="Garnerclayton"/><ref name="CMT"/><ref name="Deejays recall">{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/entertainment/story/9197593/|title=Deejays recall Garner 'Idol' contestant's early days|publisher=WRAL.com|date=March 1, 2011|access-date=March 12, 2011}}</ref> and he also sang at his middle school graduation.<ref name="Icon Competition"/> He sang [[tenor]] as a freshman in high school, where he was named Rookie of the Year. In his second year, he switched to singing [[Bass (voice type)|bass]] and began singing in his church.<ref name="maxpreps">{{cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/7emrwEzdEeCkhgAcxJSkrA/scotty-mccreery-skips-baseball-for-american-idol.htm |title=Scotty McCreery skips baseball for American Idol |publisher=Maxpreps |date=March 14, 2011 |access-date=March 14, 2011}}</ref> He also starred in a school production of ''[[Bye Bye Birdie (musical)|Bye Bye Birdie]]'' that year, playing the role of Conrad Birdie.<ref name="Garnerclayton"/> McCreery went on to join a vocal ensemble called Die Meistersingers that was formed by his high school chorus teacher, Meredith Clayton, and with which he performed across the United States.<ref name="maxpreps"/>

In 2009, McCreery won a singing contest called "Clayton Idol", which was held by [[WQDR-FM]] at the Clayton Harvest Festival in [[Clayton, North Carolina]]. After winning, he held several local shows with the radio station, raising money for sick children.<ref name="Deejays recall"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.townofclaytonnc.org/2013ClaytonIdol.aspx|title=2013 Clayton Idol – Come See the Show!|work=townofclaytonnc.org|access-date=April 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407095943/http://www.townofclaytonnc.org/2013ClaytonIdol.aspx|archive-date=April 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Later the same year, he was one of thirty-six finalists in a contest called Rip the Hallways, which featured teenage vocalists from across North Carolina.<ref name="Icon Competition"/> On the eve of Valentine's Day, 2010, McCreery performed in a variety show called Gift 4, which was held by the town of Garner.<ref name="May be a contestant">{{cite web|url=http://www.garnercitizen.com/2011/01/17/garners-scott-mccreery-may-be-american-idol-contestant/|title=Garner's Scotty McCreery may be an 'American Idol' contestant|work=Garner Citizen|date=January 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126162148/http://www.garnercitizen.com/2011/01/17/garners-scott-mccreery-may-be-american-idol-contestant/|archive-date=January 26, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shawu.edu/WSHA/Events/Events.aspx|title=February 13, 2010 – Saturday Town of Garner Presents Gift 4 Community Variety Shows|work=[[Shaw University|shawu.edu]]|access-date=April 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wptf.com/community/communitycalendar.asp?MONTHADD=-50|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140414132956/http://www.wptf.com/community/communitycalendar.asp?MONTHADD=-50|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 14, 2014|title=Community Calendar Saturday, February 13, 2010 Town of Garner Presents Gift 4, A Community Variety Show 8:00&nbsp;pm|publisher=[[WPTF]]|access-date=April 14, 2014}}</ref> In April of that year, he performed at the second annual Boots, Bands, and Bulls benefit concert. Funds from the concert went to Brittany's Battle, a Garner-based nonprofit that supports those affected by cancer. The concert was held in Raleigh, and country singer [[Jason Michael Carroll]] also performed.<ref name="May be a contestant"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.garnercitizen.com/2010/02/24/brittanys-battle-hosts-second-boots-bands-bulls-concert/|title=Brittany's Battle hosts second Boots, Bands & Bulls concert|work=Garner Citizen|date=February 24, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605050639/http://www.garnercitizen.com/2010/02/24/brittanys-battle-hosts-second-boots-bands-bulls-concert/|archive-date=June 5, 2011}}</ref>

Growing up, McCreery attended First Baptist Church in Garner. He led the church's youth praise band, Audience of One.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmaworld.com/news/2013/02/the-cma-foundation-donates-1-2-million-to-metro-nashville-public-schools-through-cmas-keep-the-music-playing-music-education-program/|title=CMA FOUNDATION DONATES $1.2 MILLION TO METRO NASHVILLE PUBLIC SCHOOLS|work=cmaworld.com|date=February 20, 2013|access-date=April 13, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brnow.org/News/June-2011/Garner-church-celebrates-American-Idol?feed=blogs|first= Dianna L.|last= Cagle|title=Garner church celebrates American Idol|work=brnow.org|date=June 6, 2011|access-date=April 13, 2014}}</ref> In addition to his musical pursuits, McCreery was a member of his high school baseball team. His coach, Derik Goffena said of him, "He doesn't throw terribly hard. His best pitch is a curveball as far as getting people out. If he had to start he probably wouldn't walk more than one or two in a game."<ref name="maxpreps"/> McCreery was working as a bagger at [[Lowes Foods]] when he auditioned for ''American Idol''.<ref name="The Pilot"/>

==''American Idol''==
===Overview===
[[File:Scotty McCreery May 14 2011 CROPPED2.jpeg|thumb|right|175px|McCreery in 2011]]
McCreery auditioned for the tenth season of ''American Idol'' in [[Milwaukee]], at the age of sixteen. He originally planned on auditioning in Nashville, but decided not to when he discovered that the date conflicted with an annual church camp. He sang "[[Your Man (Josh Turner song)|Your Man]]" by [[Josh Turner]] and "[[Put Some Drive in Your Country]]" by [[Travis Tritt]] for his audition,<ref name="In the Tour Bus"/> and then reprised "Your Man" for his first Hollywood Week performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/02/11/american-idol-recap-hollywood-week-round-one-season-10/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol Recap: Numbers Games|work=TVLine|date=February 11, 2011|access-date=April 15, 2014}}</ref> For the subsequent Group Round, he joined with Jacee Badeaux, Frances Coontz, Clint Jun Gamboa, and Monique de los Santos. Calling themselves "The Guaps", they chose to perform "[[Get Ready (The Temptations song)|Get Ready]]" by [[The Temptations]]. However, during a late stage of their preparation, Gamboa decided that Badeaux was not contributing enough to the group and forced him to leave. Before the performance, McCreery apologized to the judges for letting this happen. All five singers advanced to the next round.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Hollywood Round #2|series=American Idol|network=[[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]|date=February 16, 2011|season=10|number=9}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/american-idol-season-10-episode-9-hollywood/5/|first=Annie|last=Barrett|title=American Idol recap: Groups Gone Wild|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 17, 2011|access-date=April 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/reality-rocks/idol-insanity-the-hollywood-week-group-rounds-10-most-dramatic-moments.html|first=Lyndsey|last=Parker|title='Idol' Insanity: The Hollywood Week Group Round's 10 Most Dramatic Moments|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=February 16, 2011|access-date=April 15, 2014}}</ref>

For his second Hollywood Week solo performance, McCreery sang "[[I Hope You Dance (song)|I Hope You Dance]]" by [[Lee Ann Womack]]. He was not familiar with the lyrics and forgot them onstage. Afterward, he said that he did not feel that he deserved to go forward in the competition. The judges decided to give him another chance though,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.music.yahoo.com/blogs/reality-rocks/idol-recap-saving-the-best-and-worst-for-last.html|first=Lyndsey|last=Parker|title='Idol' Recap: Saving The Best (And Worst) For Last|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=February 17, 2011|access-date=April 15, 2014}}</ref> and following a well-received performance of Josh Turner's "[[Long Black Train]]", selected him as one of the twenty-four contestants that would move forward to the voting rounds of the competition.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/american-idol-season-10-episode-12/3/|first=Annie|last=Barrett|title=American Idol recap: 500 Miles to Seacrest|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 25, 2011|access-date=April 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title=Top 24 Chosen|series=American Idol|network=Fox|date=February 24, 2011|season=10|number=12}}</ref>

McCreery did not venture far out of the country genre throughout the competition,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/19/american-idol-recap-top-3-performance-haley-lauren-scotty/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol Recap: Destiny's Riled?|work=TVLine|date=May 19, 2011|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/24/idoloonies-lauren-alaina-scotty-mccreery-american-idol-finale-haley-bbbbennie/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=Idoloonies: Hoping for Surprises in a Haley-Free, Lauren Vs. Scotty Finale|work=TVLine|date=May 24, 2011|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/26/american-idol-season-10-finale-recap-results-scotty-lauren-winner/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol Season Finale Recap: Low and Steady Wins the Race|work=TVLine|date=May 26, 2011|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref> although one of his most acclaimed performances was of [[Carole King]]'s "[[You've Got a Friend]]".<ref name="Top 6 Parker">{{cite web|url=https://ca.music.yahoo.com/blogs/reality-rocks/idol-top-6-night-the-contestant-who-would-be-king.html|first=Lyndsey|last=Parker|title='Idol' Top 6 Night: The Contestant Who Would Be King|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=April 27, 2011|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.yahoo.com/blogs/reality-rocks/the-top-10-american-idol-performances-of-season-10.html|first=Lyndsey|last=Parker|title=The Top 10 'American Idol' Performances Of Season 10|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=May 21, 2011|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Michael Slezak">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/24/american-idol-season-10-top-performances/#!4/idol18_scotty_ygaf/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol: The Top 20 Performances from Season 10|work=TVLine|date=May 24, 2011|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref><ref name="tvline.com">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/04/28/american-idol-recap-top-6-season-10-carole-king/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol Recap: Kings of King|work=TVLine|date=April 28, 2011|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref> Taking note of [[American Idol (season 8)|season eight]] winner [[Kris Allen]]'s success with a stripped-down version of the rap song "[[Heartless (Kanye West song)|Heartless]]", McCreery considered doing an acoustic version of a hip-hop or R&B song, such as "[[So Sick]]" by [[Ne-Yo]] or something by [[Charlie Wilson (singer)|Charlie Wilson]]. Instead, he went with [[Montgomery Gentry]]'s "[[Gone (Montgomery Gentry song)|Gone]]", a country song with rap-like cadences.<ref name="Slezak Interview">{{cite interview|last=McCreery|first=Scotty|work=Idoloonies|type=video interview|url=http://tvline.com/2011/06/08/idoloonies-scotty-mccreery-american-idol-season-10-winner-interview/|title=Idoloonies: Scotty McCreery on Eyebrow Action, Showmances, Explicit Gaga, Hip-Hop Covers|date=June 8, 2011|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref> It was regarded by some as his best moment of the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/24/american-idol-season-10-top-performances/#!13/idol09_scotty_gone/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol: The Top 20 Performances from Season 10|work=TVLine|date=May 24, 2011|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Franklin Top 10 of Season">{{cite web|url=http://www.ydtalk.com/idolchatteryd/the-10-best-idol-performances-of-season-10/|first=Mark|last=Franklin|title=The 10 best Idol performances of Season 10|work=Idol Chatter|date=May 21, 2011|access-date=April 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419025315/http://www.ydtalk.com/idolchatteryd/the-10-best-idol-performances-of-season-10/|archive-date=April 19, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>

On making the Top 3, McCreery and the other remaining finalists earned celebratory hometown visits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/20/american-idol-recap-top-3-results-haley-lauren-scotty/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol Recap: Oh But She's Weird and She's Wonderful|work=TVLine|date=May 20, 2011|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref> While back in Garner, McCreery made an appearance at his high school's prom, threw the first pitch at a baseball game between the [[North Carolina State Wolfpack]] and the [[Florida State Seminoles baseball|Florida State Seminoles]], and performed for a crowd of around thirty-thousand at Lake Benson Park. He was joined by his guitar teacher, Gary Epperson and Epperson's band, Gavinhart.<ref name="Garnerclayton"/> As McCreery was singing Josh Turner's "Your Man", Turner himself surprised McCreery onstage and joined him for the song.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/471566/american-idol-top-3-visit-hometowns-judges-choice-songs-revealed|first=Cortney|last=Wills|title='American Idol' Top 3 Visit Hometowns, Judges' Choice Songs Revealed|magazine=Billboard|date=May 15, 2011|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/idolchatter/post/2011/05/josh-turner-surprises-scotty-mccreery-during-hometown-visit/1#.U1Mq0_ldWkF|first=Brian|last=Mansfield124|title=Josh Turner surprises Scotty McCreery during hometown visit|work=Idol Chatter|date=May 17, 2011|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref>

McCreery entered the finale with fellow country singer [[Lauren Alaina]],<ref name="Weird and Wonderful">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2011/05/20/american-idol-recap-top-3-results-haley-lauren-scotty/|first=Michael|last=Slezak|title=American Idol Recap: Oh But She's Weird and She's Wonderful|work=TVLine|date=May 20, 2011|access-date=April 23, 2014}}</ref> with whom he had shared duets several times that season.<ref name="Michael Slezak"/><ref name="tvline.com"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/american-idol-season-10-episode-22-results/|first=Annie|last=Barrett|title=American Idol recap: Goodbye Yellow Brick Road|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=March 31, 2011|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/american-idol-season-10-episode-27/|first=Jessica|last=Shaw|title=American Idol recap: Guy's Night Out|magazine=Entertainment Weekly|date=April 15, 2011|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref> This was the youngest match-up in the history of the series. Alaina was sixteen at the time, and McCreery had turned seventeen since auditioning.<ref name="Weird and Wonderful"/> He went on to become the series' youngest male winner and second youngest winner overall, after [[American Idol (season 6)|season six]]'s [[Jordin Sparks]], who was also seventeen when she won.<ref name="CMT"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/american-idol-crowns-scotty-mccreery-season-10-winner-050931797.html|title='American Idol' Crowns Scotty McCreery Season 10 Winner|publisher=Yahoo! News|date=May 26, 2011|access-date=April 23, 2014}}</ref> Because of his age, McCreery had to have one of his parents live with him throughout the competition; usually his mother. They lived in a mansion with the other contestants for a short time, but moved into an apartment of their own before the end of the series.<ref name="Garnerclayton"/>

