==Career==
[[File:American Idol Tour Season 10 Scotty McCreery.jpg|thumb|270px|Season 10 ''American Idol'' tour, Scotty McCreery performing with [[Thia Megia]], [[Haley Reinhart]] and [[Pia Toscano]]]]

McCreery released his coronation single "[[I Love You This Big]]" immediately after winning the tenth season of ''American Idol''.  The song entered the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart at number 32, becoming the highest debut for a debut single since the chart converted to BDS data the week of January 20, 1990.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/470941/scotty-mccreery-makes-historic-start-lauren-alaina-bows-on|title=Scotty McCreery Makes Historic Start, Lauren Alaina Bows On Country Songs|magazine=Billboard|date=May 30, 2011|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> The song sold 171,404 units in its first week,<ref name="prnews June 3, 2011">{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/scotty-mccreery-makes-history-with-debut-single-i-love-you-this-big-123094363.html |title=Scotty McCreery Makes History With Debut Single, "I Love You This Big" |agency=PR Newswire |date=June 3, 2011 |access-date=June 3, 2011}}</ref> and was certified gold on August 25, 2011. A music video for the song, shot on Angels Point near Dodger Stadium, was released on August 9, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1668715/scotty-mccreery-music-video-i-love-you-this-big.jhtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503015438/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1668715/scotty-mccreery-music-video-i-love-you-this-big.jhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 3, 2012|title='American Idol' Winner Scotty McCreery Releases Debut Video|publisher=MTV|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiponline.com/10760/american-idol-winner-scotty-mccreerys-music-video-for-i-love-you-this-big.html|title=American Idol Winner Scotty McCreery's Music Video for "I Love You This Big"|website=Hiponline.com|access-date=May 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408214336/http://www.hiponline.com/10760/american-idol-winner-scotty-mccreerys-music-video-for-i-love-you-this-big.html|archive-date=April 8, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>

He signed with Mercury Nashville,<ref name="zap2it June 1, 2011">{{cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2011/06/american-idol-scotty-mccreery-and-lauren-alaina-sign-with-mercury-nashville.html |title='American Idol': Scotty McCreery and Lauren Alaina sign with Mercury Nashville |publisher=zap2it |date=June 1, 2011 |access-date=June 1, 2011}}</ref> earning a contract that gave him over $250,000 in advances for recording the first album.<ref name="billboard May 26, 2011">{{cite news |url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/legal-and-management/american-idol-draft-contracts-reveal-big-1005205202.story |title='American Idol' Draft Contracts Reveal Big Paydays for Scotty McCreery, Lauren Alaina |agency=Associated Press |date=May 26, 2011 |access-date=June 1, 2011 |archive-date=June 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630060916/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/legal-and-management/american-idol-draft-contracts-reveal-big-1005205202.story |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Both McCreery and [[Lauren Alaina]] were invited to present at the [[CMT Music Awards]] on June 8, 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/idolchatter/post/2011/06/scotty-mccreery-lauren-alaina-pretty-much-everywhere-at-cma-music-fest/1|title=Scotty McCreery, Lauren Alaina pretty much everywhere at CMA Music Fest|website=USA Today|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> and they also both performed on the [[Grand Ole Opry]] on June 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opry.com/news/2011/06-10.html|title=American Idol Winner Scotty McCreery and Runner-up Lauren Alaina Make Their Grand Ole Opry Debuts|website=Opry.com|access-date=May 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207215913/http://www.opry.com/news/2011/06-10.html|archive-date=December 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1665067/scotty-mccreery-books-opry-leno-good-morning-america.jhtml|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606074156/http://www.cmt.com/news/news-in-brief/1665067/scotty-mccreery-books-opry-leno-good-morning-america.jhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 6, 2011|title=Scotty McCreery Books Opry, Leno, Good Morning America|publisher=Country Music Television|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> McCreery performed "I Love You This Big" and George Strait's song "Check Yes or No."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehollywoodgossip.com/2011/06/scotty-mccreery-and-lauren-alaina-grand-ole-opry-performances/|title=Scotty McCreery & Lauren Alaina: Grand Ole Opry Performances|date=June 12, 2011|website=Thehollywoodgossip.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Their trip to Nashville was also featured later in an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Special ''CMA Music Fest: Country's Night to Rock'' where McCreery performed "Your Man" with Josh Turner at the [[CMA Music Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theboot.com/2011/06/12/lauren-alaina-and-scotty-mccreery-cma-music-fest/|title=Lauren Alaina, Scotty McCreery Steal the Show at CMA Music Fest|website=The Boot|date=June 12, 2011 |access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>

McCreery toured with the [[American Idols LIVE! Tour 2011]], which began in [[West Valley City, Utah]], on July 6, 2011, and ended in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]] on September 21, 2011.

McCreery recorded [[Tim McGraw]]'s "[[Please Remember Me]]" and it was released on March 8, 2012. It was used as the exit song on the [[American Idol (season 11)|eleventh season]] of ''American Idol''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mjsbigblog.com/scotty-mccreery-sings-american-idol-11-exit-song-please-remember-me-snip.htm |title=Scotty McCreery – American Idol 11 Exit Song "Please Remember Me" (Snip) |date=March 7, 2012 |publisher=Mjsbigblog.com |access-date=March 26, 2012}}</ref>

===2011: ''Clear as Day''===
[[File:Scotty McCreery.jpg|thumb|220px|left|McCreery performing in 2011.]]
McCreery's debut album, ''[[Clear as Day]]'', was released on October 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-lauren-alaina-album-release-date/|title=Scotty McCreery and Lauren Alaina Announce Release Date and Title of New Albums|website=Taste of Country|date=August 12, 2011 |access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> Tracks from the album include a song from [[Keith Urban]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.boston.com/2011-08-27/ae/29936173_1_lauren-alaina-haley-reinhart-keith-urban/2|title=Staying country strong|website=Boston Globe|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> and the title track "Clear as Day".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-clear-as-day-demo-phil-odonnell/|title=Scotty McCreery's 'Clear As Day' Demo Reportedly Discovered Online|website=Taste of Country|date=August 13, 2011 |access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> McCreery aimed to include an explicitly Christian song in that album and he included the song "Old King James," which dwells on a Bible being passed down for generations.<ref name="Christian Post">{{cite news|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/country-star-scotty-mccreery-im-not-ashamed-of-my-faith-113282/ |title=Country Star Scotty McCreery: I'm Not Ashamed of My Faith |newspaper=[[The Christian Post]] |date=January 24, 2014 |access-date=January 20, 2014}}</ref> On October 3, 2011, the day before his debut album was scheduled to be released, [[Great American Country|GAC]] premiered a TV special, ''Introducing: Scotty McCreery''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/american-idol/blogger/fans-of-scotty/scotty-mccreery-already-getting-a-gac-tv-special-500055649.aspx|title=American Idol – Premier Blogger Article|website=Buddytv.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>

The album sold 197,000 on its debut week, and McCreery made history as the first country act to debut at No. 1 on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with their first studio album, as well as the youngest man to open at the top of the chart with his debut release.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts-articles/chart-alert/american-idol-winner-scotty-mccreery-makes-1005400952.story|title=Billboard biz|magazine=Billboard|access-date=May 8, 2018|archive-date=May 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530045904/http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts-articles/chart-alert/american-idol-winner-scotty-mccreery-makes-1005400952.story|url-status=dead}}</ref> It reached No. 1 on five separate ''Billboard'' charts – Billboard 200, Top Current Albums, Digital Albums, Internet Albums, and Top Country Albums. With the debut album ''Clear as Day'' reaching number one on the Billboard 200, he joined [[Kelly Clarkson]], [[Ruben Studdard]], [[Clay Aiken]], [[Carrie Underwood]], [[Chris Daughtry]] and [[Adam Lambert]] as the only ''Idol'' contestants to have a number one album. ''Clear as Day'' has since been certified platinum with over 1 million units shipped.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/idolchatter/post/2012/01/scotty-mccreery-platinum/1 |title=Scotty McCreery's album goes platinum |work=USA Today |date=January 10, 2012 |access-date=January 19, 2012}}</ref>

Before the release of his album, a single from this album, "[[The Trouble with Girls (song)|The Trouble with Girls]]", was premiered on radio on August 30, 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nashville.com/music/2011/08/scotty-mccreery-releases-new-single/|title=Scotty McCreery Releases New Single|website=Nashville.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>
On October 1, 2011, McCreery filmed music video for "The Trouble with Girl" at his high school in his hometown of Garner, North Carolina.
[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/idolchatter/post/2011/08/scotty-mccreery-debuts-new-single-the-trouble-with-girls/1 Scotty McCreery debuts new single, 'The Trouble With Girls']</ref> and released onto iTunes on September 1, 2011.  The news that "The Trouble with Girls", along with the album ''Clear as Day'', had been certified gold coincided with McCreery's appearance on ''[[Today (NBC program)|Today]]'' on November 23, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/showbiz/s91/american-idol/news/a352589/american-idol-scotty-mccreery-still-deciding-on-college-plans.html |title='American Idol' Scotty McCreery still deciding on college plans – American Idol News – Showbiz |website=Digital Spy |date=November 23, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> The next day, the Thanksgiving Day of 2011, McCreery performed "The Trouble With Girls" at the 85th [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] in New York City then headlined the Macy's Great Tree Lighting at Lenox Square Mall in Atlanta in the evening.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countrymusicrocks.net/2011/11/scotty-mccreery-to-headline-macys-annual-lenox-square-christmas-tree-lighting.html |title=Scotty McCreery To Headline Macy's Annual Lenox Square Christmas Tree Lighting |publisher=Country Music Rocks |date=November 24, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>

On November 9, 2011, McCreery performed a track from his album, "Walk in the Country", and announced the CMA Radio Stations of the Year honors at the 45th Annual [[Country Music Association Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-walk-in-the-country-2011-cma-awards |title=Scotty McCreery Thanks Radio After Singing 'Walk in the Country' at 2011 CMA Awards |publisher=Tasteofcountry.com |date=November 9, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> The next day McCreery joined other country stars in Nashville to tape the CMA Country Christmas special that aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on December 1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/cma-country-christmas-pictures |title='CMA Country Christmas' Preview: Faith Hill, Scotty McCreery + More Perform |newspaper=Taste of Country |publisher=Tasteofcountry.com |date=November 11, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> He performed "[[The First Noel]]", which was included in his Christmas album the following year, during the second annual ''CMA Country Christmas''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/12/02/thursday-final-ratings-no-adjustment-for-community-bones-or-any-thursday-original/112501/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205011840/http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/12/02/thursday-final-ratings-no-adjustment-for-community-bones-or-any-thursday-original/112501/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 5, 2011 |title=Thursday Final Ratings: No Adjustment for 'Community,' 'Bones' or Any Thursday Original – Ratings &#124; TVbytheNumbers |publisher=Tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>

On October 19, 2011, McCreery sang the [[The Star-Spangled Banner|National Anthem]] in Game 1 of the [[2011 World Series|World Series]] between the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] and [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] at [[Busch Stadium]] in [[St. Louis]]. He also performed on the [[Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade]] at [[Walt Disney World]] on December 25, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-tapes-disney-christmas-day-parade-segment/ |title=Scotty McCreery Tapes Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade Segment |newspaper=Taste of Country |publisher=Tasteofcountry.com |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>

McCreery was nominated and won the first of his awards at the 2nd Annual [[American Country Awards]] on December 5, 2011.<ref name="allaccess1">{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/99381/alabama-to-be-honored-at-american-country-awards-w |title=Alabama To Be Honored at American Country Awards With 'Greatest Hits Award' &#124; |publisher=Allaccess.com |date=November 22, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> He performed his second single at the award show and won in the New Artist category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-trouble-with-girls-2011-american-country-awards/ |title=Scotty McCreery Accepts First Award, Performs 'The Trouble With Girls' at 2011 American Country Awards |first=Billy |last=Dukes |publisher=Taste of Country |date=December 5, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> He also won the Best New Artist award at the [[Academy of Country Music Awards|ACM Awards]] on April 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-best-new-artist-2012-acm-awards/ |first=Cristin |last=Maher |title= Scotty McCreery Snags Most Fan Votes to Win Best New Artist at 2012 ACM Awards|publisher=Taste of Country |date=April 1, 2012 }}</ref> He received the Breakthrough Video of the Year Award at the [[CMT Music Awards]] on June 6, 2012.<ref name="graduation">{{cite news |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/06/06/2118117/scotty-mccreery-gets-cmt-award.html |title=Scotty McCreery gets CMT award as graduation gift |first= Thad |last= Ogburn |publisher=newobserver.com |date=June 7, 2012 }}</ref>

===2012: ''Christmas with Scotty McCreery''===
In 2012, he opened for [[Brad Paisley]] along with [[The Band Perry]]. The tour kicked off on January 12 with tour dates announced for the first quarter of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countrymusicislove.com/2011/10/brad-paisley-announces-2012-world-tour.html |title=Brad Paisley Announces 2012 World Tour-Country Music Is Love |publisher=Countrymusicislove.com |date=October 19, 2011 |access-date=December 27, 2011}}</ref>

''[[Christmas with Scotty McCreery]]'', was released on October 16, 2012. The album includes nine holiday classics and two new holiday songs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theboot.com/2012/07/30/scotty-mccreery-holiday-album/ |title= Scotty McCreery Holiday Album in the Works |first=Gayle |last=Thompson |publisher=The Boot |date=July 30, 2012 }}</ref> It debuted at No. 4 on Billboard 200 with sales of 41,000,<ref name="Idol Chatter 10-24-2012">{{cite news|title=Scotty McCreery's Christmas album debuts at No. 4 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/idolchatter/2012/10/24/scotty-mccreery-christmas-album-sales/1654283/ |last=Mansfield |first=Brian |work=Idol Chatter |date=October 24, 2012 |access-date=October 24, 2012}}</ref> and was certified gold on November 26, 2012.{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|type=album|title=Christmas With Scotty McCreery|artist=Scotty McCreery}} The Christmas album was included in the ''Scotty McCreery QVC Bundle'', which also contains ''Clear as Day'', released through [[QVC]], and sold 5,000 copies the first week.<ref name="roughstock_Nov7">{{cite news |url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/country-album-chart-news-for-november-7-2012-cma-awards-impact-taylor-swift-red-sells-340-000-more |title=Country Album Chart News For November 7, 2012: CMA Awards Impact; Taylor Swift "Red" Sells 340,000 more |first=Matt |last=Bjorke |publisher=Roughstock |date=November 7, 2012 |access-date=November 7, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110233839/http://www.roughstock.com/blog/country-album-chart-news-for-november-7-2012-cma-awards-impact-taylor-swift-red-sells-340-000-more |archive-date=November 10, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> McCreery also hopes to make more Christmas albums in the future.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/473997/scotty-mccreery-eyes-more-christmas-albums-in-his-future |title= Scotty McCreery Eyes More Christmas Albums in His Future
|first=Chuck |last=Dauphin |date= November 27, 2012 |magazine=Billboard }}</ref>

McCreery performed a track from the album, "Holly Jolly Christmas" and "[[Jingle Bells]]" in the [[Rockefeller Center Christmas Tree|Christmas in Rockefeller Center]] special broadcast on [[NBC]] on November 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-holly-jolly-christmas-rockefeller/|title= Scotty McCreery Ignites a 'Holly Jolly Christmas' Season at Rockefeller Center|first=Megan |last=Pacella |date= November 29, 2012|publisher=Taste of Country|access-date=January 6, 2013 }}</ref> He also sang "[[Winter Wonderland]]" at the CMA Country Christmas show aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on December 20, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.americanidol.com/news/view/pid/10534/ |title=Scotty McCreery and Keith Urban to Perform on CMA Country Christmas|publisher=americanidol.com|date=October 16, 2012|access-date=January 6, 2013 }}</ref> He performed [[Santa Claus Is Back in Town]] and [[Mary, Did You Know?]] at the "Christmas in Washington" gala, an annual seasonal celebration benefiting the Children's National Medical Center attended by the President.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/12/22/christmas-in-washington-obamas-psy/ |title=Christmas in Washington: Diana Ross, Demi Lovato, PSY entertain the Obamas, America |first=Ray |last=Rahman |magazine=EW.com|date=December 22, 2012 |access-date=January 6, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.mjsbigblog.com/scotty-mccreery-demi-lovato-chris-mann-christmas-in-washington-video.htm |title=Scotty McCreery, Demi Lovato, Chris Mann – Christmas in Washington – VIDEO|publisher=mjsbigblog|date=December 22, 2012 }}</ref>

===2013–2015: ''See You Tonight''===
McCreery's second album, ''[[See You Tonight]]'', was released on October 15, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/american-idol/articles/2013-08-07-scotty-mccreerys-sophomore-album-october-15|first=Carson|last=Blackwelder|title=Scotty McCreery's Sophomore Album Due Out on October 15?|work=Wet Paint|date=August 7, 2013|access-date=April 7, 2015}}</ref> The album was produced by [[Frank Rogers (record producer)|Frank Rogers]]. Its [[See You Tonight (song)|title track]] was released in May of that year as the lead single, and became McCreery's first song to reach the top ten on ''Billboard'''s Hot Country Songs chart.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/5915505/cole-swindell-scores-first-hot-country-songs-no-1/ |first=Wade |last=Jessen |title= Cole Swindell Scores First Hot Country Songs No. 1|magazine=Billboard |date=February 20, 2014 }}</ref> McCreery wrote the song with [[Ashley Gorley]] and [[Zach Crowell]]. "[[Feelin' It (Scotty McCreery song)|Feelin' It]]" was released as the second single in April 2014<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-feelin-it/|title=Scotty McCreery, 'Feelin' It' [Listen]|work=Taste of Country|date=April 1, 2014|access-date=April 19, 2014}}</ref> and debuted at number fifty-four on the Country Airplay chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/idol-worship/american-idol-charts-season-10-697832|first=Fred|last=Bronson|title='American Idol' on the Charts: Season 10 Alums Scotty McCreery, James Durbin Return|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 21, 2014|access-date=April 21, 2014}}</ref> The single reached the top ten on Billboard Country Airplay.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6405556/raelynn-luke-bryan-leap-country-charts |first=Wade |last=Jessen |title= RaeLynn & Luke Bryan Leap On Country Charts|magazine=Billboard |date=December 11, 2014 }}</ref>

===2015–2019: Departure from Mercury, ''Go Big or Go Home'', and ''Seasons Change''===
In August 2015, McCreery released the single "[[Southern Belle (song)|Southern Belle]]", which was intended as the lead single for a third Mercury album.<ref>{{cite web|title=Roughstock|date=August 17, 2015|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/08/37045-scotty-mccreerys-southern-belle-hits-itunes|access-date=August 17, 2015}}</ref> The single failed to gain much traction on the radio, peaking at No. 45 on Billboard Country Airplay. On February 3, 2016, it was confirmed that McCreery had parted ways with Mercury.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dukes|first1=Billy|title=Scotty McCreery Parts Way With Label|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-leaves-universal-music-group/|website=Taste of Country|date=February 3, 2016 |publisher=Taste of Country Network|access-date=February 3, 2016}}</ref> He mentored two semi-finalists during the fifteenth season of ''American Idol.'' McCreery sang with Jeneve Rose Mitchell on "[[Gone (Montgomery Gentry song)|Gone]]" and with Jenna Renae on his own "[[See You Tonight]]". On April 7, 2016, he returned to American Idol for the original series' final show, performing a country medley with Idol alumni Kellie Pickler, Lauren Alaina, Kree Harrison, Bucky Covington, Constantine Maroulis, Ace Young, Diana DeGarmo, and Skylar Laine.

He wrote a book, ''Go Big or Go Home,'' which was released May 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Scotty McCreery Releases First Book: The Ram Report|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/scotty-mccreery-releases-first-book-the-ram-report-20160504|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=May 4, 2016|access-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref> He describes the book as a travelogue about specific memories throughout his life. He went on a book tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery Plans 'Go Big or Go Home' Book Tour|url=http://theboot.com/scotty-mccreery-book-tour-2016/|work=The Boot|date=April 7, 2016 |access-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref>

McCreery signed a new management deal with Triple 8 on October 24, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery Joins Triple 8, Adds Scott Stem For Day-To-Day Management|url=https://musicrow.com/2016/10/scotty-mccreery-joins-triple-8-adds-scott-stem-for-day-to-day-management/|work=Music Row|access-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref> McCreery released his new single, "[[Five More Minutes (Scotty McCreery song)|Five More Minutes]]" to digital retailers and streaming services on May 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=5 Things Scotty McCreery Wants You to Know About His New Song, "5 More Minutes"|url=http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2017/05/05/5-things-scotty-mccreery-wants-you-to-know-about-his-new-song-5-more-minutes/|work=Nash Country Daily|date=May 5, 2017|access-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref> The song was co-written by McCreery, Frank Rogers, and Monty Criswell, after the passing of his grandfather. On June 12, 2017, McCreery released a music video for the single which includes home videos of his life.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Watch Scotty McCreery's Poignant '5 More Minutes' Video|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/scotty-mccreerys-5-more-minutes-watch-video-w487989|magazine=Rolling Stone|date=June 14, 2017|access-date=August 12, 2017}}</ref> "Five More Minutes" is the first song released without a record label to ever chart on the Country Aircheck/Mediabase Top 50.<ref name="chatter">{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery Signs with Triple Tigers Records/ Sony Music Entertainment|url=http://www.countryschatter.com/2017/08/scotty-mccreery-signs-with-triple-tigers-records-sony-music-entertainment/|work=Country's Chatter|date=August 15, 2017|access-date=August 15, 2017}}</ref> On August 15, 2017, McCreery signed a new label deal with Triple Tigers Records/Sony Music Entertainment.<ref name="chatter"/> In January 2018, "Five More Minutes" became McCreery's first number one single on the country singles charts. On August 5, 2018, McCreery appeared on "[[Celebrity Family Feud]]" and won $25,000 for his charity, [[St. Jude Children's Research Hospital]].<ref name="$25,000">{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery Wins $25,000 For St. Jude Children's Research Hospital on Celebrity Family Feud|url=http://www.soundslikenashville.com/news/scotty-mccreery-st-jude-family-feud/|work=Sounds Like Nashville|date=August 7, 2018|access-date=August 27, 2018}}</ref> McCreery released his second single, "[[This Is It (Scotty McCreery song)|This Is It]]", to digital retailers on March 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to Scotty McCreery's New Engagement-Inspired Single, "This Is It"|url=http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2018/03/09/listen-to-scotty-mccreerys-new-engagement-inspired-single-this-is-it/|last=Casey|first=Jim|work=Nash Country Daily|date=March 9, 2018|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The single peaked at number one on the Billboard Country Airplay and Mediabase Country charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery 'This Is It' Hits No. 1|url=https://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-this-is-it-charts/|work=Taste of Country|date=February 12, 2019 |access-date=October 5, 2019}}</ref> McCreery released his third single, "[[In Between (Scotty McCreery song)|In Between]]", to radio on April 1, 2019,<ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to Scotty McCreery's New Single, "In Between"|url=http://www.nashcountrydaily.com/2019/03/13/listen-to-scotty-mccreerys-new-single-in-between/|last=Casey|first=Jim|work=Nash Country Daily|date=March 13, 2019|access-date=November 9, 2019}}</ref> which later became his third consecutive number one on both the Billboard Country Airplay and Mediabase Country charts.

===2020–2022: ''Same Truck''===
"[[You Time]]" was released on September 23, 2020<ref>{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery's New Single, 'You Time,' Is a Love Letter To His Wife, Gabi|url=https://www.countrynow.com/scotty-mccreerys-new-single-you-time-is-a-love-letter-to-his-wife-gabi/|work=Country Now|date=September 3, 2020|access-date=September 23, 2020}}</ref> as the first single to his fifth studio album, ''[[Same Truck]],'' which was released on September 17, 2021.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Scotty McCreery Readies His Fifth Studio Album 'Same Truck'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/scotty-mccreery-new-album-same-truck-1200805/|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 22, 2021|first=Jon|last=Freeman}}</ref> "[[Damn Strait]]" was released on October 18, 2021, as the second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaccess.com/country/future-releases|title=Future Releases for Country Radio Stations|website=AllAccess|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20211018231716/https://www.allaccess.com/country/future-releases|archivedate=October 18, 2021|accessdate=October 18, 2021}}</ref> A deluxe version was released that included the single "[[It Matters to Her]]" that peaked at No. 3 on the [[Country Airplay|country airplay]] chart. 

=== 2023–present: ''Rise & Fall'' ===
McCreery released the single "[[Cab in a Solo]]" on August 18, 2023 as the lead single to his sixth studio album, ''[[Rise & Fall (album)|Rise & Fall]].'' It reached number one in May of 2024 ahead of the release of the album. ''[[Rise & Fall (album)|Rise & Fall]]'' was received with positive reviews and commercial success, drawing comparisons to 90's country.

==Personal life==
McCreery is a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref>{{cite web |date=June 8, 2011 |title=McCreery, Alaina Talk Music, Faith With Rolling Stone, Christian News |url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/mccreery-alaina-talk-music-faith-with-rolling-stone-50993/ |access-date= |work=The Christian Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nashville.com/music/2011/06/scotty-mccreery-wants-faith-to-be-a-part-of-his-album/ |title=Scotty McCreery Wants Faith To Be A Part Of His Album " Nashville Music Scene |publisher=Nashville.com |access-date=December 27, 2011 |archive-date=March 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315094837/http://www.nashville.com/music/2011/06/scotty-mccreery-wants-faith-to-be-a-part-of-his-album/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> He graduated from [[Garner Magnet High School]] in 2012,<ref name="graduation"/> and attended [[North Carolina State University]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina]], pursuing a bachelor's degree in communications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/scotty-mccreery-to-attend-north-carolina-state-university/|title=Scotty McCreery to Attend North Carolina State University|date=March 31, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Gail|last=Mitchell|title=Learning Experience|magazine=Billboard|date=October 5, 2013|id = {{ProQuest|1473702878}}}}</ref> Although he is one fourth Puerto Rican, he does not speak Spanish fluently, and regrets that he did not learn the language when he was younger.<ref name="This is my new life!"/> In September 2017, McCreery became engaged to his longtime girlfriend Gabi Dugal.<ref>{{cite web |date=September 26, 2017 |title=Scotty McCreery proposes to longtime girlfriend |url=http://www.wral.com/scotty-mccreery-proposes-to-longtime-girlfriend-/16975757/ |access-date= |website=Wral.com}}</ref> They were married on June 16, 2018, in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web |date=June 16, 2022 |title=Scotty McCreery Marries Longtime Girlfriend Gabi Dugal in North Carolina – All the Details! |url=https://people.com/country/scotty-mccreery-marries-gabi-dugal-first-photo/ |website=People.com}}</ref> In June 2022, McCreery and his wife Gabi announced that they were expecting their first child, a baby boy, in November. Their son was born on October 24, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date=June 21, 2022 |title=Scotty McCreery and Wife Gabi Expecting First Baby — a Boy!: 'We Got a Little Man on the Way' |url=https://people.com/parents/scotty-mccreery-wife-gabi-pregnant-expecting-first-baby-boy-exclusive/ |access-date= |website=People.com |language=}}</ref>

===Influences===
McCreery said that during his childhood, he listened to [[Merle Haggard]], [[George Jones]], and [[Conway Twitty]]; and he cites [[Elvis Presley]] as his greatest musical influence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K-0dIy7tYX4| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210035620/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K-0dIy7tYX4&gl=US&hl=en| archive-date=2013-02-10 | url-status=dead|title=YouTube|via=YouTube|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>

===Personal interests===
McCreery is an avid sports fan and is a particular fan of the [[Carolina Hurricanes]], as well as the [[Boston Red Sox]] and [[New England Patriots]] — his father having grown up in the Boston area.<ref name="Got Country Online">{{cite web|title=Scotty McCreery Hoping Boston Strong Feeling Continues With World Series Title|url=http://www.gotcountryonline.com/2013/10/30/scotty-mccreery-hoping-boston-strong-feeling-continues-with-world-series-title/|publisher=Dan Van|access-date=January 23, 2014}}</ref> He is an avid fan of [[NC State Wolfpack]] sports, having been raised in the greater Raleigh area and attended NC State University.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Willet|first1=Robert|title=Scotty McCreery on NC State basketball, family and rooting for the Wolfpack|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/latest-news/article202204739.html|website=Newsandobserver.com|access-date=April 3, 2018}}</ref>

McCreery sang the [[Star Spangled Banner|National Anthem]] before the Patriots AFC divisional game on January 16, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/01/13/country-star-scotty-mccreery-being-patriots-fan|title=Country star Scotty McCreery on being a Patriots fan|date=January 13, 2016|website=Patriots.com|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> On October 4, 2013, he began blogging for [[Major League Baseball]],<ref name="MLBlogs Network">{{cite web|title=McCreery on the Majors|url=http://scottymccreery.mlblogs.com/|access-date=January 23, 2014}}</ref> continuing to blog for the remainder of the [[2013 Major League Baseball season]].

